post_text: Briggs is pleased to announce that starting Tuesday, September 8, meal service will transition to SFSP (Summer Food Service Program). This transition will allow us to serve meals (breakfast and lunch) to all children aged 18 and under. Children do not need to be Briggs students to participate. Meals are available for pick-up at the gym lobby from 9:00-10:00 a.m. In addition, meal delivery routes will operate from 9:00 a.m.-12:00 p.m. Children participating will receive a breakfast and lunch. Names of children will need to be provided for purposes of USDA documentation. See the schedule below for delivery stops and approximate times. Please contact the school at 918-456-4221 (ext. 100) if you need meals and are unable to pick-up or meet at one of the delivery locations.

For your information:

Oklahoma Human Services (OKDHS) and the Oklahoma State Department of Education (OSDE) worked together to create a state plan ensuring that every eligible household across the state could access benefits without needing to complete an application. P-EBT benefits will be issued for the 44-day period that schools were closed at the end of the 2019-2020 school year from March 17 through May 15, 2020.

You will receive your P-EBT benefit at your own mailing address. This is not part of a school program. If you have questions please refer to http://www.okdhs.org/library/news/rel/Pages/comm07072020.aspx

post_text:
Briggs, along with several other Cherokee County schools, have decided to delay the start of school for students until Thursday, August 27, 2020. This will allow more time for our staff to prepare for the extraordinary task before us and to acquire needed supplies and materials. School staff will still report on August 10, 2020, for professional development and preparation for the school year.

As a reminder, enrollment is now open with three options: traditional on-site learning, virtual (off-site at home) learning, and a blended on/off-site option. Please contact the school at 918-456-4221, ext. 100 if you need to enroll or check/update the enrollment status of your child. The delayed start will also allow additional time to prepare technology devices and provide orientation for virtual students.
We will provide an updated school calendar in the coming days. Thank you for your understanding during these unprecedented times.

post_text: Briggs was notified on Monday, June 8, 2020, that a food handler tested positive for COVID-19. Due to this incident, meal service has been suspended until further notice. Appropriate steps are being taken to minimize the impact of those involved. At this time, we do not have any reason to believe that those who have participated in meal service are at risk of exposure. Due to the nature of the virus, it is highly unlikely that transmission could occur from touching objects or surfaces (food items, sacks). If you have any questions or concerns, you can contact the school at 918-456-4221.

post_text: Distance learning packets will be distributed on Monday, April 6th. We will be utilizing our bus routes to deliver these packets, along with pickup at school during the hours from 9am-12pm and 1pm-3pm. If you normally pick up food on the bus route deliveries, then your packet will be delivered on the bus route. If you normally pick up food at school or have not been receiving meals, your packet will be at school for pick up from 9am-12pm or 1pm-3pm (no meals will be given during the 1pm-3pm time slot). If the above options are not feasible for you, contact the school immediately at 918-456-4221 so we can make appropriate arrangements to get your learning packets to you. Along with the packets will be personal items your child may have left at school. Also, we have included, with your packets, supplemental resources for you to keep. Understand there are no directions for these supplemental resources.

post_text:
The Flu Season is upon us. Health Protocols and Briggs School Policies state:

1. If your child is running a fever, has diarrhea, and/or vomiting you must keep them home.
2. In order for your child to return to school, they must be fever free for 24 hours without taking any fever reducing medications. Help keep illness from spreading by following the two mentioned protocols/policies.

Also, have your child wash their hands with soap and water frequently throughout the day. Thank you for your cooperation and support in the fight against the FLU this season.

The Flu Season is upon us. Health Protocols and Briggs School Policies state:

1. If your child is running a fever, has diarrhea, and/or vomiting you must keep them home.
2. In order for your child to return to school, they must be fever free for 24 hours without taking any fever reducing medications. Help keep illness from spreading by following the two mentioned protocols/policies.

Also, have your child wash their hands with soap and water frequently throughout the day. Thank you for your cooperation and support in the fight against the FLU this season.

post_text:
Pizza and water will be served to parents and students! 6th, 7th, and 8th grade parents Draw the Line/ Respect the Line meeting is tonight at 5:45 in the Briggs Cafeteria presented by the National Indian Women's Health Resource Center.

The 6th-8th grade program deals with resisting peer pressure, having good communication skills and decision making skills. The 7th and 8th grade program will include lessons regarding abstinence. These lessons will be taught by certified teachers through the National Indian Women's Health Resource Center starting January 25th.

A full page letter was sent home with students last week. (Any new enrollees were sent a letter yesterday) To opt out of receiving this curriculum you will need to return the opt out form on the bottom of that informational letter by January 17th.

This is for 6th, 7th, and 8th grade students only. Draw the Line/ Respect the Line curriculum is presented by the National Indian Women's Health Resource Center. The 6th-8th grade program deals with resisting peer pressure, having good communication skills and decision making skills. The 7th and 8th grade program will include lessons regarding abstinence. These lessons will be taught by certified teachers through the National Indian Women's Health Resource Center.

A full page letter was sent home with students last week. To opt out of receiving this curriculum you will need to return the opt out form on the bottom of that informational letter by January 17th.

We will have a parent meeting Wednesday, January 15th at 5:45 in the cafeteria to go over the program and answer any questions you may have. School personnel will have student care available in the gymnasium, while parents attend the meeting in the cafeteria. Pizza and water will be available in the cafeteria.
